solution.p:
The first piece of information given tells us \ds\diff{f}{x}=\pi f(x). Then by Theorem,


f(x)&=Ce^{\pi x}

for some constant C. The second piece of given information tells us
f(0)=2. Using this, we can solve for C:
2&=f(0)=Ce^{0}=C

Now, we know f(x) entirely:
f(x)&=2e^{\pi t}

So, we can evaluate f(2)
f(2)&=2e^{2\pi}

for some constant T(0).
We can check that this is reasonable: if T(t)&=\left[T(0)+\frac{9}{7}\right]e^{7t}-\frac{9}{7}
then \diff{T}{t}&=7\left[T(0)+\frac{9}{7}\right]e^{7t}
&=7\left[T+\frac{9}{7}\right]
&=7T+9.

Let Q(t) denote the amount of radioactive material after t days. Then Q(t)=Q(0)e^{kt}. We are told
Q(8)&=0.8\,Q(0)
So, Q(0)e^{8k}&=0.8\,Q(0)
e^{8k}&=0.8
e^k&=0.8^{\tfrac{1}{8}}
If Q(0)=100, the time t at which Q(t)=40 is determined by 40=Q(t)&=Q(0)e^{kt}=100e^{kt}=100\left(0.8^{\tfrac{1}{8}}\right)^t=100\cdot 0.8^{\tfrac{t}{8}}
Solving for t: \frac{40}{100}&=0.8^{\tfrac{t}{8}}
\log\left(0.4\right)&=\log\left(0.8^{\tfrac{t}{8}}\right)=\frac{t}{8}\log(0.8)
t&=\frac{8\log(0.4)}{\log(0.8)}\approx 32.85\mbox{ days}
100 grams will decay to 40 grams in about 32.85 days.

(a) We want our differential equation to have the format of the equation in Corollary:
\frac{dv}{dt}(t)&=-g-kv(t)
&=-k\left(v(t)+\frac{g}{k}\right)
&=-k\left(v(t)-\left(-\frac{g}{k}\right)\right)
So, we can use the corollary, with K=-k, T=v, and A=-\dfrac{g}{k}. v(t)&=\left(v(0)-\left(-\frac{g}{k}\right)\right)e^{-kt}-\frac{g}{k}
&=\left(v_0+\frac{g}{k}\right)e^{-kt}-\frac{g}{k}
